        <div xml:id="KT18-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">iravukkuṟi vantu nīṅkun talaimakaṉait tōḻi etirppaṭṭu varaivu kaṭāyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">The confidante inquiring about marriage after having appeared in front of HIM who leaves after having come to the night-tryst.</p>
          </div>

        <div xml:id="KT18">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                vēral vēli vērkkōṭ palaviṉ</l>
<l>                cāra ṉāṭa cevviyai yākumati</l>
<l>                yāraḵ taṟintici ṉōrē cāraṟ</l>
<l>                ciṟukōṭṭup perumpaḻan tūṅkiyāṅkiva</l>
<l>                ḷuyirtavac ciṟitu kāmamō peritē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <l>O man from the slope</l>
                <l rend="indent">of jackfruit trees, bearing down to the root in a bamboo fence,</l>
                <l rend="indent4">come in time!<note place="foot">Strange is here the wording <term xml:lang="ta">cevviyai ākumati</term>, literally "please become the season". A.D. considers the possibility of taking it literal and understand it as a metaphor: "please become the (rainy) season", i.e. the time where HE usually comes back, which would mean here the time to marry HER.</note></l>
                <l>Who knows?<note place="foot">The meaning of this question is unclear. Cām. glosses atu with <term xml:lang="ta">annilaiyai</term> <q>that state</q>, so it might be: "who has understood that condition (SHE is in)?" Another possibility might be: "who knows (what will/can happen)?"</note></l>
                <l rend="indent2">Like at the slope</l>
                <l rend="indent">on a small twig a big fruit her</l>
                <l>life very small, but desire big.</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
